  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The interstate relocation is one of the higher-stakes property transactions a Brisbane family will ever undertake. You are not simply selling a home; you are sequencing two transactions in two different states, with two solicitors, two banks, and two very different property markets, while also managing the logistics of physically relocating a household and often a family. The difference between a well-sequenced interstate move and a poorly sequenced one can easily run to six figures in bridging finance, stamp duty exposure, and missed pricing opportunities on either side.</p>

      <p>The good news is that the decision framework is well established. Most families settle on one of three structural approaches: sell in Brisbane first and buy in the new city later, buy in the new city first and sell Brisbane under time pressure, or aim for a simultaneous settlement where both transactions close on or near the same day. Each has a clear profile of pros and cons, and the right choice depends on your risk tolerance, your financial capacity, and the specific markets on both ends of the move.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who this article is for</h2>
      <p>If you are a Brisbane homeowner preparing to relocate interstate for work, family, lifestyle or retirement, and you need to sell your Brisbane home and purchase a replacement in the destination city, this article lays out the three strategic options and the practical steps for each. The most common destinations from Brisbane are Sydney, Melbourne, Perth, and Adelaide, though the principles apply to Canberra, Hobart, and Darwin as well. Regional moves within Queensland raise some of the same issues but with less state-level complexity to navigate.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option 1: Sell Brisbane first, then buy interstate</h2>
      <p>Selling first is the most common and generally the lowest-financial-risk option. You list and sell the Brisbane property, settle, and then use the proceeds to purchase in the new city. In the gap between settlements, you rent short-term in the new city while actively searching.</p>

      <p>The advantages are significant. You know your exact sale proceeds before you commit to a purchase, which eliminates the risk of overcommitting to the new property. You avoid bridging finance costs entirely, which for a Brisbane to Sydney or Brisbane to Melbourne move can easily exceed $1,500 to $2,500 per month while you carry two mortgages. You arrive in the new city as a cash-ready buyer, which materially improves your negotiating position and gives you access to purchases that require flexible settlement terms.</p>

      <p>The disadvantages are mostly practical. You have to move twice: from Brisbane to a short-term rental, and then from the rental into the permanent home. With children, pets, and accumulated belongings, the double move carries both financial cost and emotional disruption. You are also exposed to property price rises in the destination city during your search, which in hot Sydney or Melbourne markets can consume more than you would have paid in bridging interest. And the short-term rental market in inner Sydney and Melbourne is expensive and competitive, with many landlords unwilling to offer leases shorter than twelve months.</p>

      <p>This option works best when the destination market is stable or soft, when you have genuine flexibility on the timing of your permanent purchase, and when you can tolerate a six to eight week rental period without significant family disruption. It is the default recommendation for retirees, downsizers, and relocators whose new city situation does not demand an immediate settled home.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option 2: Buy interstate first, then sell Brisbane</h2>
      <p>Buying first is the fastest route to a single move and a settled family, but it is also the most financially exposed option. You identify and purchase the new home in the destination city, settle on it using bridging finance or a deposit bond combined with existing equity, then list the Brisbane home and sell under time pressure to repay the bridging facility.</p>

      <p>The advantages are mostly about family life. A single move preserves school continuity, avoids the short-term rental market, and lets the family settle into permanent housing as soon as you arrive. You secure the specific property you want in the new city rather than hoping the right home is available when you arrive. For families with children mid-school-year or pets that do not travel well, this is often the option that minimises household disruption.</p>

      <p>The financial disadvantages are substantial. Bridging finance is expensive. Most Australian lenders offer bridging terms of six to twelve months at interest rates between 1.5 and 3 per cent above standard variable home loan rates. On a typical Brisbane to Sydney buy-first scenario, the bridging facility may run to $1.5 to $2 million to cover the Sydney purchase while the Brisbane home is sold, producing monthly interest exposure of $7,000 to $12,000 depending on how long the Brisbane sale takes.</p>

      <p>You are also under pressure to sell Brisbane quickly, which routinely depresses the sale price by 3 to 8 per cent relative to a patient, well-run campaign. The combination of bridging interest plus a discounted sale can easily reach $50,000 to $100,000 on a single move. Against this, the savings in short-term rental costs, moving costs, and family disruption may be $15,000 to $30,000. The buy-first option tends to leave families financially worse off than buying-first advocates assume.</p>

      <p>Buy-first works best where the destination market is genuinely time-limited (a specific property is listed that will not come up again), where the buyer has strong equity and income so bridging costs are absorbed comfortably, or where family circumstances make the single move non-negotiable. Employer-sponsored relocations with relocation packages that cover bridging costs can also change the maths.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Option 3: Simultaneous settlement</h2>
      <p>A simultaneous settlement is the ideal theoretical outcome: the Brisbane sale and the interstate purchase settle on the same day, with the sale proceeds flowing directly into the purchase. No bridging, no short-term rental, no double move. It is also the most logistically demanding option and requires a level of coordination that many sellers underestimate.</p>

      <p>The introduction of PEXA electronic settlement across Australia has made simultaneous settlements materially more achievable than they were a decade ago. PEXA allows solicitors and banks to coordinate the settlement workspace in real time across state lines, and both Brisbane and the major interstate capitals are on PEXA for residential conveyancing. What previously required manually coordinated bank cheques exchanged by couriers is now an electronic process that can be timed to the hour.</p>

      <p>The challenge is synchronising the two contracts. You need buyers in Brisbane who are prepared to exchange with a settlement date that matches your ability to secure the interstate purchase, and you need a vendor in the destination city who is prepared to exchange with a settlement date that aligns with your Brisbane sale. Finding both simultaneously is a matter of careful campaign sequencing rather than luck.</p>

      <p>The usual approach is to list the Brisbane property first, secure a buyer, and negotiate a settlement date that is long enough (usually 60 to 90 days) to give you time to find and secure the interstate purchase. You then purchase in the new city with a settlement date matching your Brisbane sale. Solicitors in both states are briefed on the arrangement from the outset and coordinate through the contract conditions. On settlement day, the Brisbane sale clears, the proceeds transfer through PEXA to the purchase-side bank, and the interstate purchase closes within the same electronic session.</p>

      <p>The risks are real. If the Brisbane buyer pulls out, the interstate purchase may proceed without matching funds, forcing either bridging finance at short notice or contract termination with penalty. If the interstate vendor demands an earlier settlement, you may be forced to pay without the Brisbane proceeds in hand. Careful contract drafting, including simultaneous-settlement conditions and suitable cooling-off provisions, is essential. This is not a DIY arrangement; it requires experienced conveyancers in both states.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Market differences between Brisbane and the major interstate capitals</h2>
      <p>The mechanical differences between the Brisbane market and the major destination markets affect your sequencing decisions.</p>

      <p>Settlement timing conventions differ. Brisbane contracts typically settle 30 to 45 days after exchange, with private treaty being the dominant sale method. Sydney and Melbourne contracts often run 42 to 90 days, particularly for auction sales where the standard deposit-on-fall-of-hammer structure works with a longer settlement. Perth and Adelaide sit closer to Brisbane timing but with their own regional variations. Building these differences into your simultaneous-settlement planning is essential.</p>

      <p>Auction prevalence differs. Sydney and Melbourne are strong auction markets, with a substantial share of inner-metropolitan residential sales going through public auction. The auction campaign runs for a shorter period (typically three to four weeks) but the purchase process itself requires unconditional bidding on auction day, without cooling-off, with a 10 per cent deposit on the fall of the hammer. If you are buying in Sydney or Melbourne, budget for the possibility that you will bid at auction and plan your finance pre-approval accordingly. Perth and Adelaide remain predominantly private treaty markets.</p>

      <p>Pricing dynamics differ. Brisbane has historically been a more stable market than Sydney and Melbourne, with less pronounced cycle peaks and troughs. A buy-first strategy into Sydney or Melbourne at the wrong part of the cycle can expose you to a falling price on the Brisbane sale while the Sydney or Melbourne purchase also moves against you. Being aware of where each market sits in its cycle is part of the strategic calculation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The capital gains tax position</h2>
      <p>For most relocators, the Brisbane home being sold has been the principal place of residence and is eligible for the main residence exemption under the Capital Gains Tax (CGT) provisions of the Income Tax Assessment Act. Provided the home has been your main residence for the entire period of ownership, the sale is free of CGT regardless of the capital gain.</p>

      <p>Where it gets more complex is around the timing of the move. The main residence exemption can be extended for up to six years where the property is rented out after you move, provided you have not nominated another property as your main residence in that period. If the interstate move involves renting the Brisbane home before selling, this six-year rule can preserve the exemption. The interaction between the Brisbane property's exemption and the new interstate home's exemption has rules around when each starts and stops.</p>

      <p>The rules also allow a six-month overlap where you own both your old and new main residences simultaneously. Buy-first relocators often use this window, but it has technical conditions including that both properties must have been main residences and the old one must have been a main residence for at least three months in the twelve months before sale. If you are considering buy-first, get CGT advice specific to your dates before committing, not after.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Employer-sponsored relocations</h2>
      <p>If the interstate move is employer-sponsored, the terms of the relocation package materially change the financial analysis. Typical employer relocation packages cover temporary accommodation (usually 30 to 90 days of furnished rental), removalist and freight costs, one or more house-hunting trips, and in some cases a stamp duty contribution toward the destination property. Senior relocation packages may also cover bridging finance interest, sale agent fees, and capital gains tax liability where the move is time-compressed.</p>

      <p>Relocation terms are negotiable before signing the role, and much harder to improve after. If you are accepting a relocation offer, ask explicitly about the sell-side support, the temporary accommodation allowance, whether bridging finance is covered, and whether any stamp duty contribution is made. The value of a well-structured relocation package can easily exceed $50,000 to $100,000 for a senior role; forgoing that is not a sensible way to demonstrate enthusiasm for the new job.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Practical preparation timeline</h2>
      <p>For a relocation targeting a specific move date, the practical timeline starts 12 to 16 weeks out. That timeline allows for 4 to 6 weeks of campaign preparation (styling, photography, marketing), 4 to 6 weeks of active campaign time, and 4 to 6 weeks of settlement.</p>

      <p>Twelve weeks out, engage solicitors in both states, start property research in the new city, and begin gathering comparable sales data for your Brisbane home. Ten weeks out, begin preparing the Brisbane home for sale and book photography and marketing. Eight weeks out, launch the Brisbane campaign and plan a property inspection trip in the new city. Four weeks out, target exchange on the Brisbane sale and identify the preferred interstate purchase. Two weeks out, coordinate settlements if pursuing a simultaneous approach.</p>

      <p>A compressed timeline (under 12 weeks) is achievable but increases execution risk on every element. A longer timeline (16 to 20 weeks) gives you more optionality and almost always produces a better net outcome.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Most families successfully completing a Brisbane to interstate relocation use either a simultaneous settlement (Option 3) or a sell-first approach with a short-term rental in the destination city (Option 1). The buy-first option (Option 2) is the least common outside employer-sponsored scenarios, because the bridging finance cost and the pressure on the Brisbane sale price rarely justify the convenience of a single move.</p>

      <p>If you are early in the planning process, engage a Brisbane agent with experience in interstate moves and a property solicitor who has run simultaneous settlements in the past. The agent's role is not only to sell your Brisbane home but to help structure the contract conditions on both ends of the move to support whichever strategy you choose. A few hours of strategic conversation at the start saves months of friction later.</p>

